  <h2 class="hidden">Find Ways to Pay for College</h2>
  <h3><img class="headline" src="<?php bloginfo('template_directory'); ?>/style/images/forStudentsFindWaysHeader.png" alt="Find Ways to Pay for College" /></h3>
  <p>Just about everybody gets some money to help them pay for college. But in order to find out how much you can get for college, you need to first determine what you&#8217;re eligible to receive. The first step is to complete the <a href="http://www.Fafsa.ed.gov">FAFSA form</a> (which stands for the Free Application for Federal Student Aid) to find out how much money you are eligible to receive to go to college. If you go to fill out a FAFSA form, you&#8217;ll need:</p>
  <ul class="bulletedList">
    <li>Your Social Security Number or Alien Registration Number if you&#8217;re not a U.S. citizen </li>
    <li>Your Driver&#8217;s License Number (if you have one)</li>
    <li>W-2 forms from the last two years</li>
    <li>Your 1040 Federal Tax Income Return (as well as your parents&#8217; tax return if you are a dependent child)</li>
    <li>Records of Untaxed Income (i.e., TANF, Social Security, Welfare or Veterans Benefits)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
  <p> The deadline for completing the FAFSA in order to qualify for PA state grants is May 1st for 4 year colleges, and August 1st for 2 year and trade colleges. Some colleges allocate aid on a first come first serve basis, so make sure to get your FAFSA completed as soon as possible. 
  <p>
  <p>There are organizations out there that can help you fill out these forms and let you know how much financial aid you can get to go to college. The <a href="http://www.fafsa4caster.ed.gov">FAFSA Forecaster</a> predicts what aid may be available to you. 
    <p>
      <a href="http://www.thebenefitbank.com/TaxCenter">The Benefit Bank</a> is a service available in the community that helps Philadelphians complete their taxes and apply for other services. People who use The Benefit Bank (TBB) to file their tax returns can use the TBB's auto-fill feature to automatically fill in the FAFSA form. 
      <p>
      The <a href="http://www.phillyfreetaxes.org/taxhelp/howtofile.asp">Campaign for Working Families</a> provides free tax completion assistance if your income meets certain guidelines. Some of their walk-in assistance sites will also help you complete the FAFSA.</p>
    <p>If you need assistance completing the FAFSA, you may attend one of the free workshops happening all over the city as part of the <a href="http://www.phillygoes2college.org/home/campaign" target=blank>City-Wide FAFSA Completion and Financial Aid Campaign</a>. <a href="/category/events/month">Check out our calendar</a> to find a workshop near you.</p>
            <p>
You can also visit a Trusted Center during designated hours for assistance. <a href="http://www.phillygoes2college.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/FAFSA-trusted-centers.pdf" target=blank>Click here to download a list of Trusted Centers.</a>
<br>
              <p>
    <span style="font-size:medium"><strong>Tax Credits for College</strong></span>
    <p>
      The American Opportunity Tax Credit offers a rebate of up to $2,500 for college expenses. To qualify for this credit you must earn under $80,000 if you file as single, or under $160,000 if you file as married. The $2,500 credit can be claimed by parents for each child that is in college, or, if the student files their taxes as an independent, by students themselves. <a href="http://www.phillygoes2college.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/American-Opportunity-Credit.pdf" target=blank>Click here to download a document with more details on how to file for this credit.</a>
    
    
    
  <a name="scholarships"></a>
  <h3 style="padding-top: 52px; border-top: 1px solid #B7B7B7;"><img class="headline" src="<?php bloginfo('template_directory'); ?>/style/images/forStudentsPG2CScholarshipsHeader.png" alt="Philly Goes To College Scholarship Resources" /></h3>
  <p style="margin-bottom: 12px;">Remember, for anybody going to college, there are dollars available from at least three sources (after you determine what you&#8217;re eligible for): money from the state where you live, money from the federal government and scholarships from the college where you want to go to school. Here are the Top 5 things you need to do before you apply for any scholarship: </p>
  <ol class="cheatSheet">
    <li>
      <span>If you are applying for college scholarships and you also need financial aid, you must first complete the FAFSA application.  </span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span>Your local library has books and information on scholarship information and is a great resource. <a href="/category/events/month">Check out free workshops</a> sponsored by the library on college-going topics.</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span>Once you have been admitted to college, ask the financial aid specialists at that school if there are specific scholarships you may apply for.  Don&#8217;t assume they will just tell you!</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span>Each year millions of dollars in scholarships go unassigned.  Be careful to look at the criteria needed to apply such as age, race, religion, specific interest, etc.  There just might be a scholarship right for you!</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span>Scholarship providers do not charge a fee for submitting an application or recommending a scholarship to which you want to apply.  Beware of scams!</span>
    </li>
  </ol>
